y layer for Claude Code. Today it's fully open source under MIT.**\n\n  Line 31: - 🧩 **Provider-agnostic** — one core (`@rohirik/openltm-core`), thin adapters per host.\n\n  Line 34: > Migrating from an earlier install? The marketplace is now [`RohiRIK/OpenLtm`](https://github.com/RohiRIK/OpenLtm) and the plugin is `openltm`. Your existing memory database carries over.\n\n  Line 68: claude plugin install openltm\n\n  Line 71: Restart Claude Code. That's it. Four Claude Code hooks + one git post-commit hook auto-wire, four commands load, five skills activate, and your `openltm.db` migrates or creates itself.\n\n  Line 76: bunx @rohirik/openltm-core          # auto-detect Claude Code, OpenCode\n\n  Line 77: bunx @rohirik/openltm-core --pi     # experimental Pi adapter\n\n  Line 78: bunx @rohirik/openltm-core --dry-run --claude  # preview without writing\n\n  Line 97: /openltm:memory recall auth       — what do we know about auth in this project?\n\n  Line 98: /openltm:memory learn <insight>   — save something worth keeping\n\n  Line 99: /openltm:health                   — memory health + decay summary\n\n  Line 100: /openltm:project init             — set a goal for the current project\n\n  Line 113:    ├── 5 Skills    ──┼──▶  openltm MCP server ──▶  openltm.db\n\n  Line 127: /openltm:health                    # plugin health + hooks + decay\n\n  Line 128: /openltm:memory recall test        # returns results (or \"no results\" on fresh install)\n\n  Line 131: Start a new session — you should see context injected at the top. If not, run `/openltm:health` to diagnose.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/packages/adapter-pi/README.md:\n  Line 29: ~/.claude/plugins/data/OpenLtm-openltm/openltm.db\n\n  Line 37: export LTM_DB_PATH=\"/custom/path/openltm.db\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-sp